{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1143"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1143"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.22,0.08,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44704"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right upper quadrant pain, fever and rigors. She noticed dark urine yesterday. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She drinks one standard drink of alcohol per day and is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears severely unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant. Central venous pressure measures 2 cm H20. She has received intravenous antibiotics and a 500 mL isotonic saline bolus. One hour later, her vital signs remain unchanged and her urinary catheter output over two hours is 15 mL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous frusemide","Intravenous dopamine infusion","Intravenous adrenaline infusion","500 mL of 5% dextrose over two hours","500 mL of isotonic saline over 30 minutes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with ascending cholangitis (fever and right upper quadrant pain are two of the three components of Charcot\u0027s triad) complicated by septic shock. The low blood pressure, tachycardia, low central venous pressure, and poor urine output indicate significant hypovolaemia requiring urgent fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500 mL of isotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E given rapidly is the most appropriate next step. In septic shock, early aggressive fluid resuscitation with crystalloid is essential before considering other interventions. The previous 500 mL bolus was inadequate as evidenced by ongoing hypotension and oliguria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dopamine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous adrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E may be required later if hypotension persists despite adequate fluid resuscitation (typically 2-3 L). However, vasopressors should not be started before addressing the underlying hypovolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500 mL of 5% dextrose\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as hypotonic solutions do not effectively expand intravascular volume in shock states. Additionally, the slower infusion rate would not address the urgent need for volume replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous frusemide\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen the hypovolaemia and shock state. Diuretics are contraindicated in patients with hypotension and evidence of tissue hypoperfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial resuscitation, definitive management will require biliary decompression, typically via endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP). However, the immediate priority is stabilising the patient\u0027s haemodynamic status with fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rapid intravenous crystalloid replacement is essential first-line management in septic shock with hypovolaemia.","Cholangitis presenting with fever, right upper quadrant pain and jaundice (Charcot\u0027s triad) requires urgent fluid resuscitation and antibiotics.","Inotropic support should only be considered after adequate fluid resuscitation in septic shock."],"references":["Evans L, Rhodes A, Alhazzani W, Antonelli M, Coopersmith CM, French C, et al. Surviving sepsis campaign: international guidelines for management of sepsis and septic shock 2021. Intensive Care Med. 2021 Nov;47(11):1181-1247.Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34599691/","Treatment of Sepsis. In: Australian Sepsis Network [online]. 2018. Available at: https://www.australiansepsisnetwork.net.au/healthcare-providers/treatment-sepsis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1143"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:26:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:26:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1143"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76915"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}}